		<item>
		<title>Be Like Ludwig</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/WriterUnboxed/~3/Gt4mYJg0nxo/</link>
		<comments>http://writerunboxed.com/2014/12/10/be-like-ludwig/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Wed, 10 Dec 2014 12:00:44 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Sarah Callender]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[CRAFT]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Inspirations]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Beethoven's Fifth]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Beethoven's Wig]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Inevitability]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Leonard Bernstein]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://writerunboxed.com/?p=34636</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p class="wp-caption-text">I make this same face when someone interrupts my writing or when I am not getting enough fiber in my diet.</p>
<p>A few weeks ago, a friend was talking about a Leonard Bernstein Omnibus lecture, the one in which Bernstein discusses the power and beauty of Beethoven’s Fifth Symphony. Three Gs and an E flat. Bah Bah Bah BAAAH. Bah bah bah BAAAH.</p>
<p>Bernstein sits down at a piano and plays those four notes, explaining that while they are the theme around which Beethoven [...] <br/><div class="clearfix"></div>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- Start Shareaholic LikeButtonSetTop Automatic --><!-- End Shareaholic LikeButtonSetTop Automatic --><div id="attachment_34637" style="width: 202px" class="wp-caption alignleft"><a href="http://writerunboxed.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/3708975865_a70a73a1d8_m.jpg"><img class="wp-image-34637 size-full" src="http://writerunboxed.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/3708975865_a70a73a1d8_m.jpg" alt="3708975865_a70a73a1d8_m" width="192" height="240" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">I make this same face when someone interrupts my writing or when I am not getting enough fiber in my diet.</p></div>
<p>A few weeks ago, a friend was talking about a Leonard Bernstein Omnibus lecture, the one in which Bernstein discusses the power and beauty of <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_4IRMYuE1hI">Beethoven’s Fifth Symphony</a>. Three Gs and an E flat. <em>Bah Bah Bah BAAAH. Bah bah bah BAAAH</em>.</p>
<p>Bernstein sits down at a piano and plays those four notes, explaining that while they are the theme around which Beethoven builds the entire symphony, they alone do not make the piece so powerful. Rather, Bernstein says, the Fifth has universal appeal because each note feels inevitable based on the note that precedes it. Huh! Quite an accomplishment for a deaf fellow with huge hair and an even bigger scarf/collar situation.</p>
<p>And Bernstein is correct. Whether the score includes a C-sharp or a fermata over a dotted half note, we listeners sense there is nothing that could fit more perfectly or precisely. The result? A composition of notes so thoughtfully arranged that they create an ordered, satisfying, musical story.</p>
<p>I think that&#8217;s why we gravitate toward great art: at its most basic level, great art creates a story that is comprised of one inevitable, satisfying beat after another. When each note (or brushstroke or word) feels inevitable, it reminds us that even with the chaos in our world: courtroom verdicts, ISIS beheadings, suicide bombers, pediatric cancer, racism and poverty, we can rely on great music, art, poetry and fiction to deliver a story that points us to order, truth, peace and justice.</p>
<p>Story keeps us breathing. Story keeps us sane. Story also makes us smarter. Albert Einstein (supposedly) said, &#8220;If you want your children to be intelligent, read them fairy tales. If you want them to be more intelligent, read them more fairy tales.&#8221; Similarly, in <em><a href="http://wiredforstory.com/">Wired for Story</a>, </em>Lisa Cron (who has the exact same IQ as Einstein), explains how story is the art form from which humans make sense of confusing, complex things. Story is art. Crafting story is also <em>an</em> art.</p>
<p>In our fiction then, how do we follow a deaf composer&#8217;s example? How do we build stories where each word, sentence, scene and plot point falls inevitably after the one that precedes it? <span id="more-34636"></span></p>
<p><strong>First, we must know where the story is going.</strong> However we craft our stories (with pants or without) we cannot replicate the Fifth’s feeling of order and inevitability if we don’t know our characters&#8217; destination. As captains of our ship-story, we need to assure the reader that we have both map and compass. Perhaps Dramamine and Chapstick. Maybe some beef jerky and juice boxes. But map and compass are crucial. Without them, we writers cannot weave a collection of beats, scenes and chapters into a conclusion that feels right and inevitable.</p>
<p>But hold on! A &#8220;right and inevitable&#8221; conclusion may not always be fair and just. Meaning, the good guy will not always win. It will <em>feel</em> fair and just, however, based on how the writer has teed up each scene. The climax and conclusion of <em>The Great Gatsby</em>, for example, may not feel fair because reckless, naughty, rich people run roughshod over innocent others. But based on the way Fitzgerald reveals the story, starting on page one, the ending with the beautiful passage, <em>So we beat on, boats against the current, borne back ceaselessly into the past</em>, the conclusion feels true. Gatsby and his gilded dreams could never have survived in Daisy&#8217;s and Tom&#8217;s world. Wealthy people have power. They escape scrutiny. Any other outcome would have felt like cotton candy, coloring our tongues blue and leaving us with sticky fingers and unsatisfied hunger.</p>
<p><strong>We must also figure out how tension and conflict propel a story.</strong>  What does the character want? Who and what stand in his way? How will he overcome the obstacles? What will happen to him as a result of getting (or not getting) what he desires? I suggest you turn to <a href="http://maassagency.com/books-on-writing/">Donald Maass&#8217; craft books</a> for a far-better-than-I-could-do explanation of how a writer creates tension and conflict. It&#8217;s <em>muy importante, amigo</em>. And Mr. Maass is a generous expert.</p>
<p><strong>Then, get out of the story&#8217;s way.</strong> A story is a magical and fierce, living and breathing, arrangement of words. It knows where it needs to go, and we need to trust its power. A curly-haired woman would never straighten her hair on an August day with 96% humidity. She knows it&#8217;s silly to fight nature. It&#8217;s equally silly to fight story. Let a story lead us on the dance floor, and it will conclude with that satisfying feeling of inevitability.</p>
<p>Make no mistake! Inevitability is not synonymous with predictability. We do not want predictable stories. Surprises in fiction&#8211;delivered via plot, dialogue, diction or sentence structure&#8211;provide delightful moments. And we don&#8217;t have to worry; striving to create a feeling of inevitability in our stories will <em>not</em> render them formulaic and prescribed.</p>
<p>I recently finished reading Anthony Marra&#8217;s <a href="http://www.goodreads.com/author/show/5989255.Anthony_Marra"><em>A Constellation of Vital Phenomena</em></a> and just finished viewing the BBC/Sundance miniseries, <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt2103085/"><em>Top of the Lake</em></a>. Both contain delightful and disturbing surprises as they move to their inevitable conclusions. Sure I would have loved a happi<em>er</em> ending in each, but my version of a happy ending would not have been true. While we may not realize it, we do seek truth in fiction.</p>
<p>But man, it is not easy to create a story that contains surprise <em>and </em>inevitability! Beethoven created fourteen discrete drafts of the Fifth over eight years. We too must revise. But how do we revise with the goal of inevitability? I don&#8217;t know exactly. There&#8217;s no recipe. I wish there were.</p>
<p>I do know it is possible. I know it requires incredible dedication and tenacity. It requires the time and desire to study others&#8217; fiction and craft books that illustrate the building blocks of scene. I know we need at least one fantastic writing partner, that we need to loosen the reigns and trust the thrum of the story. Oh, and a good gut feeling is incredibly helpful. But that&#8217;s all the advice I&#8217;ve got.</p>
<p>I&#8217;m sorry. Truly.</p>
<p>I wish there were a recipe for Inevitability &amp; Surprise that I could share here. I do have an amazing chocolate cake recipe that won my neighborhood Chocolate Cake Cook-off . . . I can send you that if you like.</p>
<p><strong>Maybe you can help by contributing YOUR ideas? What strategies do you employ to create a sense of inevitability and truth in the flow of your story? Will you share some examples of film or fiction that illustrate the feeling of inevitability? Do you know <a href="http://beethovenswig.com/">this song</a>? </strong></p>
<div class="shr-publisher-34636"></div><!-- Start Shareaholic LikeButtonSetBottom Automatic --><!-- End Shareaholic LikeButtonSetBottom Automatic --><div class="clearfix"><div class="ldc-style-10"><div class="ldc-button"><span class='ul_cont_like like' id="34636" >Like&nbsp;(<span>10</span>)</span><span class="alert-msg"></span></div></div></div> <!-- WP Biographia v3.3.2 -->
<p><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/4aa70f8341c8495f7b65336d2cd75e15?s=100&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG' class='wp-biographia-avatar avatar-100 photo' height='100' width='100' /></p><div class="wp-biographia-text"><h3>About <a href="http://writerunboxed.com/author/sarah-callender/" title="Sarah Callender">Sarah Callender</a></h3><p>Sarah Callender lives in Seattle with her husband, son and daughter and is currently working on a novel titled BETWEEN THE SUN AND THE ORANGES. Sarah is a terrible house-cleaner, a lover of chocolate and hats, and a self-professed cheapskate who has no trouble spending money on good chocolate and hats.</p><div class="wp-biographia-links"><small><a href="http://sarahrcallender.wordpress.com/" target="_blank" title="Sarah Callender On The Web" class="wp-biographia-link-">Web</a> | <a href="https://twitter.com/sarahrcallender" target="_blank" title="Sarah Callender On Twitter" class="wp-biographia-link-">Twitter</a> | <a href="http://writerunboxed.com/author/sarah-callender/" target="_blank" title="More Posts By Sarah Callender" class="wp-biographia-link-">More Posts</a></small></div></div><!-- WP Biographia v3.3.2 -->
